  55 @tf_export('keras.models.Model', 'keras.Model')
  56 class Model(Network):
  57   """`Model` groups layers into an object with training and inference features.
  58 
  59   There are two ways to instantiate a `Model`:
  60 
  61   1 - With the "functional API", where you start from `Input`,
  62   you chain layer calls to specify the model's forward pass,
  63   and finally you create your model from inputs and outputs:
  64 
  65   ```python
  66   import tensorflow as tf
  67 
  68   inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=(3,))
  69   x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation=tf.nn.relu)(inputs)
  70   outputs = tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation=tf.nn.softmax)(x)
  71   model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
  72   ```
  73 
  74   2 - By subclassing the `Model` class: in that case, you should define your
  75   layers in `__init__` and you should implement the model's forward pass
  76   in `call`.
  77 
  78   ```python
  79   import tensorflow as tf
  80 
  81   class MyModel(tf.keras.Model):
  82 
  83     def __init__(self):
  84       super(MyModel, self).__init__()
  85       self.dense1 = tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation=tf.nn.relu)
  86       self.dense2 = tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation=tf.nn.softmax)
  87 
  88     def call(self, inputs):
  89       x = self.dense1(inputs)
  90       return self.dense2(x)
  91 
  92   model = MyModel()
  93   ```
  94 
  95   If you subclass `Model`, you can optionally have
  96   a `training` argument (boolean) in `call`, which you can use to specify
  97   a different behavior in training and inference:
  98 
  99   ```python
 100   import tensorflow as tf
 101 
 102   class MyModel(tf.keras.Model):
 103 
 104     def __init__(self):
 105       super(MyModel, self).__init__()
 106       self.dense1 = tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation=tf.nn.relu)
 107       self.dense2 = tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation=tf.nn.softmax)
 108       self.dropout = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5)
 109 
 110     def call(self, inputs, training=False):
 111       x = self.dense1(inputs)
 112       if training:
 113         x = self.dropout(x, training=training)
 114       return self.dense2(x)
 115 
 116   model = MyModel()
 117   ```
 118   """
 119 
 120   def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
 121     super(Model, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
 122     # Create a cache for iterator get_next op.
 123     self._iterator_get_next = weakref.WeakKeyDictionary()
 124     # Create a cache for dataset - uninitialized iterators
 125     self._dataset_iterator_cache = weakref.WeakKeyDictionary()
 126     # initializing _distribution_strategy here since it is possible to call
 127     # predict on a model without compiling it.
 128     self._distribution_strategy = None
 129 
 130   def _set_sample_weight_attributes(self, sample_weight_mode,
 131                                     skip_target_weighing_indices):
 132     """Sets sample weight related attributes on the model."""
 133     sample_weights, sample_weight_modes = training_utils.prepare_sample_weights(
 134         self.output_names, sample_weight_mode, skip_target_weighing_indices)
 135     self.sample_weights = sample_weights
 136     self.sample_weight_modes = sample_weight_modes
 137     self._feed_sample_weight_modes = [
 138         sample_weight_modes[i]
 139         for i in range(len(self.outputs))
 140         if i not in skip_target_weighing_indices
 141     ]
 142     self._feed_sample_weights = [
 143         sample_weights[i]
 144         for i in range(len(sample_weights))
 145         if i not in skip_target_weighing_indices
 146     ]
 147 
 148   def _cache_output_metric_attributes(self, metrics, weighted_metrics):
 149     """Caches metric name and function attributes for every model output."""
 150     output_shapes = [
 151         None if output is None else output.get_shape().as_list()
 152         for output in self.outputs
 153     ]
 154     self._per_output_metrics = training_utils.collect_per_output_metric_info(
 155         metrics, self.output_names, output_shapes, self.loss_functions)
 156     self._per_output_weighted_metrics = \
 157         training_utils.collect_per_output_metric_info(
 158             weighted_metrics, self.output_names, output_shapes,
 159             self.loss_functions, self.sample_weights)
 160 
 161   def _add_unique_metric_name(self, metric_name, output_index):
 162     """Makes the metric name unique and adds it to the model's metric name list.
 163 
 164       If there are multiple outputs for which the metrics are calculated, the
 165       metric names have to be made unique by appending an integer.
 166 
 167     Arguments:
 168       metric_name: Metric name that corresponds to the metric specified by the
 169           user. For example: 'acc'.
 170       output_index: The index of the model output for which the metric name is
 171         being added.
 172 
 173     Returns:
 174       string, name of the model's unique metric name
 175     """
 176     if len(self.output_names) > 1:
 177       metric_name = '%s_%s' % (self.output_names[output_index], metric_name)
 178     j = 1
 179     base_metric_name = metric_name
 180     while metric_name in self.metrics_names:
 181       metric_name = '%s_%d' % (base_metric_name, j)
 182       j += 1
 183 
 184     return metric_name
 185 
 186   def _init_metric_attributes(self):
 187     """Initialized model metric attributes."""
 188     self.metrics_names = ['loss']
 189     self.metrics_tensors = []
 190     self.metrics_updates = []
 191     self.stateful_metric_names = []
 192     self.stateful_metric_functions = []
 193 
 194   def _set_per_output_metric_attributes(self, metrics_dict, output_index):
 195     """Sets the metric attributes on the model for the given output.
 196 
 197     Arguments:
 198       metrics_dict: A dict with metric names as keys and metric fns as values.
 199       output_index: The index of the model output for which the metric
 200         attributes are added.
 201     """
 202     for metric_name, metric_fn in metrics_dict.items():
 203       metric_name = self._add_unique_metric_name(metric_name, output_index)
 204       # Keep track of metric name.
 205       self.metrics_names.append(metric_name)
 206 
 207       # Keep track of stateful metric attributes (name and metric function).
 208       if isinstance(metric_fn, base_layer.Layer) and metric_fn.stateful:
 209         self.stateful_metric_names.append(metric_name)
 210         self.stateful_metric_functions.append(metric_fn)
 211 
 212   def _set_metric_attributes(self, outputs, skip_target_indices=None):
 213     """Sets the metric attributes on the model for all the model outputs."""
 214     skip_target_indices = skip_target_indices or []
 215     for i in range(len(outputs)):
 216       if i in skip_target_indices:
 217         continue
 218       self._set_per_output_metric_attributes(self._per_output_metrics[i], i)
 219       self._set_per_output_metric_attributes(
 220           self._per_output_weighted_metrics[i], i)
 221 
 222   def _handle_per_output_metrics(self,
 223                                  metrics_dict,
 224                                  y_true,
 225                                  y_pred,
 226                                  mask,
 227                                  weights=None):
 228     """Calls metric functions for a single output.
 229 
 230     Arguments:
 231       metrics_dict: A dict with metric names as keys and metric fns as values.
 232       y_true: Target output.
 233       y_pred: Predicted output.
 234       mask: Computed mask value for the current output.
 235       weights: Weights to be applied on the current output.
 236 
 237     Returns:
 238       A list of metric result tensors.
 239     """
 240     metric_results = []
 241     for metric_name, metric_fn in metrics_dict.items():
 242       with K.name_scope(metric_name):
 243         if isinstance(metric_fn, metrics_module.Metric):
 244           # Call the stateful metric function.
 245           if mask is not None:
 246             mask = math_ops.cast(mask, y_pred.dtype)
 247             # Update weights with mask.
 248             if weights is None:
 249               weights = mask
 250             else:
 251               # Update shape of weights if possible before adding mask.
 252               # Update dimensions of weights to match with mask if possible.
 253               mask, _, weights = metrics_module.squeeze_or_expand_dimensions(
 254                   mask, None, weights)
 255               try:
 256                 # Broadcast weights if possible.
 257                 weights = weights_broadcast_ops.broadcast_weights(weights, mask)
 258               except ValueError:
 259                 pass
 260                 # TODO(psv): Handle case when mask and weight shapes are not
 261                 # compatible.
 262               weights *= mask
 263 
 264           metric_result = metric_fn(y_true, y_pred, weights)
 265         else:
 266           # Call the stateless metric function.
 267           weighted_metric_fn = training_utils.weighted_masked_objective(
 268               metric_fn)
 269           metric_result = weighted_metric_fn(
 270               y_true, y_pred, weights=weights, mask=mask)
 271 
 272         if not context.executing_eagerly():
 273           # Keep track of metric result tensor.
 274           self.metrics_tensors.append(metric_result)
 275 
 276       metric_results.append(metric_result)
 277       is_stateful = isinstance(metric_fn,
 278                                base_layer.Layer) and metric_fn.stateful
 279       if is_stateful and not context.executing_eagerly():
 280         # Keep track of updates created by stateful metrics.
 281         self.metrics_updates += metric_fn.updates
 282     return metric_results
 283 
 284   def _handle_metrics(self,
 285                       outputs,
 286                       skip_target_indices=None,
 287                       targets=None,
 288                       sample_weights=None,
 289                       masks=None):
 290     """Handles calling metric functions.
 291 
 292     Arguments:
 293       outputs: List of outputs (predictions).
 294       skip_target_indices: Optional. List of target ids to skip.
 295       targets: List of targets.
 296       sample_weights: Optional list of sample weight arrays.
 297       masks: List of computed output mask values.
 298 
 299     Returns:
 300       A list of metric result tensors.
 301     """
 302     skip_target_indices = skip_target_indices or []
 303     metric_results = []
 304     with K.name_scope('metrics'):
 305       for i in range(len(outputs)):
 306         if i in skip_target_indices:
 307           continue
 308         output = outputs[i] if outputs else None
 309         target = targets[i] if targets else None
 310         output_mask = masks[i] if masks else None
 311         metric_results.extend(
 312             self._handle_per_output_metrics(self._per_output_metrics[i], target,
 313                                             output, output_mask))
 314         metric_results.extend(
 315             self._handle_per_output_metrics(
 316                 self._per_output_weighted_metrics[i],
 317                 target,
 318                 output,
 319                 output_mask,
 320                 weights=sample_weights[i]))
 321     return metric_results
 322 
 323   @checkpointable.no_automatic_dependency_tracking
 324   def compile(self,
 325               optimizer,
 326               loss=None,
 327               metrics=None,
 328               loss_weights=None,
 329               sample_weight_mode=None,
 330               weighted_metrics=None,
 331               target_tensors=None,
 332               distribute=None,
 333               **kwargs):
 334     """Configures the model for training.
 335 
 336     Arguments:
 337         optimizer: String (name of optimizer) or optimizer instance.
 338             See [optimizers](/api_docs/python/tf/keras/optimizers).
 339         loss: String (name of objective function) or objective function.
 340             See [losses](/api_docs/python/tf/losses).
 341             If the model has multiple outputs, you can use a different loss
 342             on each output by passing a dictionary or a list of losses.
 343             The loss value that will be minimized by the model
 344             will then be the sum of all individual losses.
 345         metrics: List of metrics to be evaluated by the model
 346             during training and testing.
 347             Typically you will use `metrics=['accuracy']`.
 348             To specify different metrics for different outputs of a
 349             multi-output model, you could also pass a dictionary,
 350             such as `metrics={'output_a': 'accuracy'}`.
 351         loss_weights: Optional list or dictionary specifying scalar
 352             coefficients (Python floats) to weight the loss contributions
 353             of different model outputs.
 354             The loss value that will be minimized by the model
 355             will then be the *weighted sum* of all individual losses,
 356             weighted by the `loss_weights` coefficients.
 357             If a list, it is expected to have a 1:1 mapping
 358             to the model's outputs. If a tensor, it is expected to map
 359             output names (strings) to scalar coefficients.
 360         sample_weight_mode: If you need to do timestep-wise
 361             sample weighting (2D weights), set this to `"temporal"`.
 362             `None` defaults to sample-wise weights (1D).
 363             If the model has multiple outputs, you can use a different
 364             `sample_weight_mode` on each output by passing a
 365             dictionary or a list of modes.
 366         weighted_metrics: List of metrics to be evaluated and weighted
 367             by sample_weight or class_weight during training and testing.
 368         target_tensors: By default, Keras will create placeholders for the
 369             model's target, which will be fed with the target data during
 370             training. If instead you would like to use your own
 371             target tensors (in turn, Keras will not expect external
 372             Numpy data for these targets at training time), you
 373             can specify them via the `target_tensors` argument. It can be
 374             a single tensor (for a single-output model), a list of tensors,
 375             or a dict mapping output names to target tensors.
 376         distribute: The DistributionStrategy instance that we want to use to
 377             distribute the training of the model.
 378         **kwargs: These arguments are passed to `tf.Session.run`.
 379 
 380     Raises:
 381         ValueError: In case of invalid arguments for
 382             `optimizer`, `loss`, `metrics` or `sample_weight_mode`.
 383     """
 384     # Validate that arguments passed by the user to `compile` are supported by
 385     # DistributionStrategy.
 386     if distribute:
 387       if not isinstance(
 388           optimizer, (tf_optimizer_module.Optimizer, optimizers.TFOptimizer)):
 389         raise NotImplementedError(
 390             'optimizer must be an instance of '
 391             'tf.train.Optimizer, not a %s' % type(optimizer))
 392       if context.executing_eagerly():
 393         raise NotImplementedError('DistributionStrategy is not supported '
 394                                   'when eager execution is enabled.')
 395       if sample_weight_mode:
 396         raise NotImplementedError('sample_weight_mode is not supported with '
 397                                   'DistributionStrategy.')
 398       if weighted_metrics:
 399         raise NotImplementedError('weighted_metrics is not supported with '
 400                                   'DistributionStrategy.')
 401       if target_tensors:
 402         raise ValueError('target_tensors is not supported with '
 403                          'DistributionStrategy.')
 404 
 405     loss = loss or {}
 406     if context.executing_eagerly() and not isinstance(
 407         optimizer, (tf_optimizer_module.Optimizer, optimizers.TFOptimizer)):
 408       raise ValueError(
 409           'optimizer must be an instance of tf.train.Optimizer, not '
 410           'a %s' % type(optimizer))
 411 
 412     self.optimizer = optimizers.get(optimizer)
 413     # We've disabled automatic dependency tracking for this method, but do want
 414     # to add a checkpoint dependency on the optimizer if it's checkpointable.
 415     if isinstance(self.optimizer, checkpointable.CheckpointableBase):
 416       self._track_checkpointable(
 417           self.optimizer, name='optimizer', overwrite=True)
 418     self.loss = loss
 419     self.metrics = metrics or []
 420     self.loss_weights = loss_weights
 421     self.sample_weight_mode = sample_weight_mode
 422     self.weighted_metrics = weighted_metrics
 423     if context.executing_eagerly() and target_tensors is not None:
 424       raise ValueError('target_tensors is not supported in Eager mode.')
 425     self.target_tensors = target_tensors
 426 
 427     # Set DistributionStrategy specific parameters.
 428     self._distribution_strategy = distribute
 429     # Reset the value of grouped_model
 430     self._grouped_model = None
 431     if self._distribution_strategy is not None:
 432       distributed_training_utils.configure_and_create_session(
 433           self._distribution_strategy)
 434     if not self.built:
 435       # Model is not compilable because it does not know its number of inputs
 436       # and outputs, nor their shapes and names. We will compile after the first
 437       # time the model gets called on training data.
 438       return
 439     self._is_compiled = True
 440 
 441     # Prepare loss functions.
 442     if isinstance(loss, dict):
 443       for name in loss:
 444         if name not in self.output_names:
 445           raise ValueError(
 446               'Unknown entry in loss '
 447               'dictionary: "' + name + '". '
 448               'Only expected the following keys: ' + str(self.output_names))
 449       loss_functions = []
 450       for name in self.output_names:
 451         if name not in loss:
 452           logging.warning(
 453               'Output "' + name +
 454               '" missing from loss dictionary. We assume '
 455               'this was done on purpose. The fit and evaluate APIs will not be '
 456               'expecting any data to be passed to "' + name + '".')
 457         loss_functions.append(losses.get(loss.get(name)))
 458     elif isinstance(loss, list):
 459       if len(loss) != len(self.outputs):
 460         raise ValueError('When passing a list as loss, '
 461                          'it should have one entry per model outputs. '
 462                          'The model has ' + str(len(self.outputs)) +
 463                          ' outputs, but you passed loss=' + str(loss))
 464       loss_functions = [losses.get(l) for l in loss]
 465     else:
 466       loss_function = losses.get(loss)
 467       loss_functions = [loss_function for _ in range(len(self.outputs))]
 468     self.loss_functions = loss_functions
 469 
 470     weighted_losses = [training_utils.weighted_masked_objective(fn)
 471                        for fn in loss_functions]
 472     skip_target_indices = []
 473     skip_target_weighing_indices = []
 474     self._feed_outputs = []
 475     self._feed_output_names = []
 476     self._feed_output_shapes = []
 477     self._feed_loss_fns = []
 478     for i in range(len(weighted_losses)):
 479       if weighted_losses[i] is None:
 480         skip_target_indices.append(i)
 481         skip_target_weighing_indices.append(i)
 482 
 483     # Prepare output masks.
 484     if not context.executing_eagerly():
 485       masks = [getattr(x, '_keras_mask', None) for x in self.outputs]
 486       if not isinstance(masks, list):
 487         masks = [masks]
 488 
 489     # Prepare loss weights.
 490     if loss_weights is None:
 491       loss_weights_list = [1. for _ in range(len(self.outputs))]
 492     elif isinstance(loss_weights, dict):
 493       for name in loss_weights:
 494         if name not in self.output_names:
 495           raise ValueError(
 496               'Unknown entry in loss_weights '
 497               'dictionary: "' + name + '". '
 498               'Only expected the following keys: ' + str(self.output_names))
 499       loss_weights_list = []
 500       for name in self.output_names:
 501         loss_weights_list.append(loss_weights.get(name, 1.))
 502     elif isinstance(loss_weights, list):
 503       if len(loss_weights) != len(self.outputs):
 504         raise ValueError(
 505             'When passing a list as loss_weights, '
 506             'it should have one entry per model output. '
 507             'The model has ' + str(len(self.outputs)) +
 508             ' outputs, but you passed loss_weights=' + str(loss_weights))
 509       loss_weights_list = loss_weights
 510     else:
 511       raise TypeError('Could not interpret loss_weights argument: ' +
 512                       str(loss_weights) + ' - expected a list of dicts.')
 513     self.loss_weights_list = loss_weights_list
 514 
 515     # Initialize model metric attributes.
 516     self._init_metric_attributes()
 517 
 518     # Initialization for Eager mode execution.
 519     if context.executing_eagerly():
 520       # Prepare sample weights.
 521       self._set_sample_weight_attributes(sample_weight_mode,
 522                                          skip_target_weighing_indices)
 523       # Save all metric attributes per output of the model.
 524       self._cache_output_metric_attributes(metrics, weighted_metrics)
 525 
 526       if target_tensors is not None:
 527         raise ValueError('target_tensors are not currently supported in Eager '
 528                          'mode.')
 529       self.total_loss = None
 530       for i in range(len(self.outputs)):
 531         if len(self.outputs) > 1:
 532           self.metrics_names.append(self.output_names[i] + '_loss')
 533 
 534       # Set metric attributes on model.
 535       self._set_metric_attributes(
 536           self.outputs,
 537           skip_target_indices=skip_target_indices,
 538       )
 539 
 540       self.targets = []
 541       for i in range(len(self.outputs)):
 542         self._feed_output_names.append(self.output_names[i])
 543       self._collected_trainable_weights = self.trainable_weights
 544       return
 545 
 546     # Prepare targets of model.
 547     self.targets = []
 548     self._feed_targets = []
 549     if target_tensors not in (None, []):
 550       if isinstance(target_tensors, list):
 551         if len(target_tensors) != len(self.outputs):
 552           raise ValueError(
 553               'When passing a list as `target_tensors`, '
 554               'it should have one entry per model output. '
 555               'The model has ' + str(len(self.outputs)) +
 556               ' outputs, but you passed target_tensors=' + str(target_tensors))
 557       elif isinstance(target_tensors, dict):
 558         for name in target_tensors:
 559           if name not in self.output_names:
 560             raise ValueError(
 561                 'Unknown entry in `target_tensors` '
 562                 'dictionary: "' + name + '". '
 563                 'Only expected the following keys: ' + str(self.output_names))
 564         tmp_target_tensors = []
 565         for name in self.output_names:
 566           tmp_target_tensors.append(target_tensors.get(name, None))
 567         target_tensors = tmp_target_tensors
 568       else:
 569         raise TypeError('Expected `target_tensors` to be '
 570                         'a list or dict, but got:', target_tensors)
 571 
 572     for i in range(len(self.outputs)):
 573       if i in skip_target_indices:
 574         self.targets.append(None)
 575       else:
 576         shape = K.int_shape(self.outputs[i])
 577         name = self.output_names[i]
 578         if target_tensors not in (None, []):
 579           target = target_tensors[i]
 580         else:
 581           target = None
 582         if target is None or K.is_placeholder(target):
 583           if target is None:
 584             target = K.placeholder(
 585                 ndim=len(shape),
 586                 name=name + '_target',
 587                 sparse=K.is_sparse(self.outputs[i]),
 588                 dtype=K.dtype(self.outputs[i]))
 589           self._feed_targets.append(target)
 590           self._feed_outputs.append(self.outputs[i])
 591           self._feed_output_names.append(name)
 592           self._feed_output_shapes.append(shape)
 593           self._feed_loss_fns.append(self.loss_functions[i])
 594         else:
 595           skip_target_weighing_indices.append(i)
 596         self.targets.append(target)
 597 
 598     # Prepare sample weights.
 599     self._set_sample_weight_attributes(sample_weight_mode,
 600                                        skip_target_weighing_indices)
 601     # Save all metric attributes per output of the model.
 602     self._cache_output_metric_attributes(metrics, weighted_metrics)
 603 
 604     # Compute total loss.
 605     total_loss = None
 606     with K.name_scope('loss'):
 607       for i in range(len(self.outputs)):
 608         if i in skip_target_indices:
 609           continue
 610         y_true = self.targets[i]
 611         y_pred = self.outputs[i]
 612         weighted_loss = weighted_losses[i]
 613         sample_weight = self.sample_weights[i]
 614         mask = masks[i]
 615         loss_weight = loss_weights_list[i]
 616         with K.name_scope(self.output_names[i] + '_loss'):
 617           output_loss = weighted_loss(y_true, y_pred, sample_weight, mask)
 618         if len(self.outputs) > 1:
 619           self.metrics_tensors.append(output_loss)
 620           self.metrics_names.append(self.output_names[i] + '_loss')
 621         if total_loss is None:
 622           total_loss = loss_weight * output_loss
 623         else:
 624           total_loss += loss_weight * output_loss
 625       if total_loss is None:
 626         if not self.losses:
 627           raise ValueError('The model cannot be compiled '
 628                            'because it has no loss to optimize.')
 629         else:
 630           total_loss = 0.
 631 
 632       # Add regularization penalties
 633       # and other layer-specific losses.
 634       for loss_tensor in self.losses:
 635         total_loss += loss_tensor
 636 
 637     # Set metric attributes on model.
 638     self._set_metric_attributes(
 639         self.outputs,
 640         skip_target_indices=skip_target_indices,
 641     )
 642     # Invoke metric functions for all the outputs.
 643     self._handle_metrics(
 644         self.outputs,
 645         masks=masks,
 646         targets=self.targets,
 647         skip_target_indices=skip_target_indices,
 648         sample_weights=self.sample_weights)
 649 
 650     # Prepare gradient updates and state updates.
 651     self.total_loss = total_loss
 652 
 653     # Functions for train, test and predict will
 654     # be compiled lazily when required.
 655     # This saves time when the user is not using all functions.
 656     self._function_kwargs = kwargs
 657 
 658     self.train_function = None
 659     self.test_function = None
 660     self.predict_function = None
 661 
 662     # Collected trainable weights, sorted in topological order.
 663     trainable_weights = self.trainable_weights
 664     self._collected_trainable_weights = trainable_weights
 665 
 666   def _check_trainable_weights_consistency(self):
 667     """Check trainable weights count consistency.
 668 
 669     This will raise a warning if `trainable_weights` and
 670     `_collected_trainable_weights` are inconsistent (i.e. have different
 671     number of parameters).
 672     Inconsistency will typically arise when one modifies `model.trainable`
 673     without calling `model.compile` again.
 674     """
 675     if not hasattr(self, '_collected_trainable_weights'):
 676       return
 677 
 678     if len(self.trainable_weights) != len(self._collected_trainable_weights):
 679       logging.warning(
 680           UserWarning(
 681               'Discrepancy between trainable weights and collected trainable'
 682               ' weights, did you set `model.trainable` without calling'
 683               ' `model.compile` after ?'))
 684 
 685   def _make_train_function(self):
 686     if not hasattr(self, 'train_function'):
 687       raise RuntimeError('You must compile your model before using it.')
 688     self._check_trainable_weights_consistency()
 689     if self.train_function is None:
 690       inputs = (self._feed_inputs +
 691                 self._feed_targets +
 692                 self._feed_sample_weights)
 693       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
 694         inputs += [K.learning_phase()]
 695 
 696       with K.name_scope('training'):
 697         with K.name_scope(self.optimizer.__class__.__name__):
 698           # Training updates
 699           updates = self.optimizer.get_updates(
 700               params=self._collected_trainable_weights, loss=self.total_loss)
 701         # Unconditional updates
 702         updates += self.get_updates_for(None)
 703         # Conditional updates relevant to this model
 704         updates += self.get_updates_for(self.inputs)
 705         # Stateful metrics updates
 706         updates += self.metrics_updates
 707         # Gets loss and metrics. Updates weights at each call.
 708         self.train_function = K.function(
 709             inputs, [self.total_loss] + self.metrics_tensors,
 710             updates=updates,
 711             name='train_function',
 712             **self._function_kwargs)
 713 
 714   def _make_test_function(self):
 715     if not hasattr(self, 'test_function'):
 716       raise RuntimeError('You must compile your model before using it.')
 717     if self.test_function is None:
 718       inputs = (self._feed_inputs +
 719                 self._feed_targets +
 720                 self._feed_sample_weights)
 721       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
 722         inputs += [K.learning_phase()]
 723       # Return loss and metrics, no gradient updates.
 724       # Does update the network states.
 725       self.test_function = K.function(
 726           inputs, [self.total_loss] + self.metrics_tensors,
 727           updates=self.state_updates + self.metrics_updates,
 728           name='test_function',
 729           **self._function_kwargs)
 730 
 731   def _make_predict_function(self):
 732     if not hasattr(self, 'predict_function'):
 733       self.predict_function = None
 734     if self.predict_function is None:
 735       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
 736         inputs = self._feed_inputs + [K.learning_phase()]
 737       else:
 738         inputs = self._feed_inputs
 739       # Gets network outputs. Does not update weights.
 740       # Does update the network states.
 741       kwargs = getattr(self, '_function_kwargs', {})
 742       self.predict_function = K.function(
 743           inputs,
 744           self.outputs,
 745           updates=self.state_updates,
 746           name='predict_function',
 747           **kwargs)
 748 
 749   def _get_iterator_get_next_tensors(self, iterator):
 750     get_next_op = self._iterator_get_next.get(iterator, None)
 751     if get_next_op is None:
 752       get_next_op = iterator.get_next()
 753       self._iterator_get_next[iterator] = get_next_op
 754     return get_next_op
 755 
 756   def _distribution_standardize_user_data(self,
 757                                           x,
 758                                           y=None,
 759                                           sample_weight=None,
 760                                           class_weight=None,
 761                                           batch_size=None,
 762                                           check_steps=False,
 763                                           steps_name='steps',
 764                                           steps=None,
 765                                           validation_split=0):
 766     """Runs validation checks on input and target data passed by the user.
 767 
 768     This is called when using DistributionStrategy to train, evaluate or serve
 769     the model.
 770 
 771     Args:
 772       x: Input data. A numpy array or `tf.data` dataset.
 773       y: Target data. A numpy array or None if x is a `tf.data` dataset.
 774       sample_weight: An optional sample-weight array passed by the user to
 775         weight the importance of each sample in `x`.
 776       class_weight: An optional class-weight array by the user to
 777         weight the importance of samples in `x` based on the class they belong
 778         to, as conveyed by `y`.
 779       batch_size: Integer batch size. If provided, it is used to run additional
 780         validation checks on stateful models.
 781       check_steps: boolean, True if we want to check for validity of `steps` and
 782         False, otherwise.
 783       steps_name: The public API's parameter name for `steps`.
 784       steps: Integer or `None`. Total number of steps (batches of samples) to
 785         execute.
 786       validation_split: Float between 0 and 1.
 787         Fraction of the training data to be used as validation data.
 788 
 789     Returns:
 790       Iterator for reading the dataset `x`.
 791 
 792     Raises:
 793       ValueError: In case of invalid user-provided data.
 794       RuntimeError: If the model was never compiled.
 795     """
 796     if sample_weight is not None and sample_weight.all():
 797       raise NotImplementedError('`sample_weight` is currently not supported '
 798                                 'when using DistributionStrategy.')
 799     if class_weight:
 800       raise NotImplementedError('`class_weight` is currently not supported '
 801                                 'when using DistributionStrategy.')
 802 
 803     # Validates `steps` argument right at the beginning since we use it to
 804     # construct the dataset object.
 805     # TODO(anjalisridhar): This may not be a valid error since we now accept
 806     # numpy array inputs. We still want to assert that we have a populated steps
 807     # parameter.
 808     if check_steps:
 809       if steps is None:
 810         raise ValueError('When using DistributionStrategy, '
 811                          'you should specify the `{steps_name}` argument.'
 812                          .format(steps_name=steps_name))
 813 
 814     first_x_value = nest.flatten(x)[0]
 815     if isinstance(first_x_value, np.ndarray):
 816       x_shape = first_x_value.shape
 817       x_dtype = first_x_value.dtype
 818       if batch_size is None:
 819         batch_size = x_shape[0] // steps
 820       if y is not None:
 821         first_y_value = nest.flatten(y)[0]
 822         x = Dataset.from_generator(lambda x=x, y=y: six.moves.zip(x, y),
 823                                    output_types=(x_dtype, first_y_value.dtype),
 824                                    output_shapes=(x_shape[1:],
 825                                                   first_y_value.shape[1:]))
 826         # TODO(anjalisridhar): What should the buffer size be?
 827         x = x.shuffle(10000)
 828         x = x.repeat()
 829         x = x.batch(batch_size)
 830         y = None
 831       else:
 832         # This case is for the predict call where the dataset only contains
 833         # inputs and no targets i.e it does not return a tuple.
 834         # TODO(anjalisridhar): Raise an error if we are not able to process
 835         # all the predict samples. This can happen if the number of batches is
 836         # not evenly divisible by the number of worker devices.
 837         x = Dataset.from_generator(lambda x=x: x,
 838                                    output_types=x_dtype,
 839                                    output_shapes=x_shape[1:])
 840         x = x.repeat()
 841         x = x.batch(batch_size)
 842 
 843     # TODO(anjalisridhar): Can we use the iterator and getnext op cache?
 844     # We require users to pass Datasets since we distribute the dataset across
 845     # multiple devices.
 846     assert isinstance(x, dataset_ops.Dataset)
 847 
 848     # TODO(anjalisridhar): We want distribute_dataset() to accept a Dataset or a
 849     # function which returns a Dataset. Currently distribute_dataset() only
 850     # accepts a function that returns a Dataset. Once we add support for being
 851     # able to clone a Dataset on multiple workers we can remove this lambda.
 852     result = self._distribution_strategy.distribute_dataset(lambda: x)
 853     iterator = result.make_initializable_iterator()
 854     with self._distribution_strategy.scope():
 855       K.get_session().run(iterator.initializer)
 856 
 857     training_utils.validate_iterator_input(x, y, sample_weight,
 858                                            validation_split)
 859     return iterator
 860 
 861   def _standardize_user_data(self,
 862                              x,
 863                              y=None,
 864                              sample_weight=None,
 865                              class_weight=None,
 866                              batch_size=None,
 867                              check_steps=False,
 868                              steps_name='steps',
 869                              steps=None,
 870                              validation_split=0):
 871     """Runs validation checks on input and target data passed by the user.
 872 
 873     Also standardizes the data to lists of arrays, in order.
 874 
 875     Also builds and compiles the model on the fly if it is a subclassed model
 876     that has never been called before (and thus has no inputs/outputs).
 877 
 878     This is a purely internal method, subject to refactoring at any time.
 879 
 880     Args:
 881       x: Input data. It could be:
 882         - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
 883           (in case the model has multiple inputs).
 884         - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
 885           (in case the model has multiple inputs).
 886         - A dict mapping input names to the corresponding array/tensors,
 887           if the model has named inputs.
 888         - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
 889       y: Target data. Like the input data `x`,
 890         it could be either Numpy array(s) or TensorFlow tensor(s).
 891         It should be consistent with `x` (you cannot have Numpy inputs and
 892         tensor targets, or inversely). If `x` is a dataset or a
 893         dataset iterator, `y` should not be specified
 894         (since targets will be obtained from the iterator).
 895       sample_weight: An optional sample-weight array passed by the user to
 896         weight the importance of each sample in `x`.
 897       class_weight: An optional class-weight array by the user to
 898         weight the importance of samples in `x` based on the class they belong
 899         to, as conveyed by `y`.
 900       batch_size: Integer batch size. If provided, it is used to run additional
 901         validation checks on stateful models.
 902       check_steps: boolean, True if we want to check for validity of `steps` and
 903         False, otherwise. For example, when we are standardizing one batch of
 904         data for train_on_batch/predict_on_batch/test_on_batch APIs, `steps`
 905         value is not required and we should not check for its validity in these
 906         cases.
 907       steps_name: The public API's parameter name for `steps`.
 908       steps: Integer or `None`. Total number of steps (batches of samples) to
 909         execute.
 910       validation_split: Float between 0 and 1.
 911         Fraction of the training data to be used as validation data.
 912 
 913     Returns:
 914       A tuple of 3: inputs (arrays or dicts, depending on whether `x` was a dict
 915       or not), target arrays, sample-weight arrays.
 916       If the model's input and targets are symbolic, these lists are empty
 917       (since the model takes no user-provided data, instead the data comes
 918       from the symbolic inputs/targets).
 919 
 920     Raises:
 921       ValueError: In case of invalid user-provided data.
 922       RuntimeError: If the model was never compiled.
 923     """
 924     if self._distribution_strategy:
 925       iterator = self._distribution_standardize_user_data(
 926           x,
 927           y,
 928           sample_weight=sample_weight,
 929           class_weight=class_weight,
 930           batch_size=batch_size,
 931           check_steps=check_steps,
 932           steps_name=steps_name,
 933           steps=steps,
 934           validation_split=validation_split)
 935       return iterator, None, None
 936 
 937     if isinstance(x, dataset_ops.Dataset):
 938       if context.executing_eagerly():
 939         x = x.make_one_shot_iterator()
 940       else:
 941         if x in self._dataset_iterator_cache:
 942           x = self._dataset_iterator_cache[x]
 943         else:
 944           iterator = x.make_initializable_iterator()
 945           self._dataset_iterator_cache[x] = iterator
 946           x = iterator
 947         K.get_session().run(x.initializer)
 948 
 949     # Validates `steps` argument based on x's type.
 950     if check_steps:
 951       training_utils.check_steps_argument(x, steps, steps_name)
 952 
 953     is_x_eager_iterator = isinstance(x, iterator_ops.EagerIterator)
 954     is_x_iterator = isinstance(x, iterator_ops.Iterator)
 955 
 956     # Validate user inputs when data is given as a dataset or dataset iterator.
 957     if is_x_iterator or is_x_eager_iterator:
 958       training_utils.validate_iterator_input(x, y, sample_weight,
 959                                              validation_split)
 960 
 961     # For eager iterators, when we have to process multiple batches of samples,
 962     # we will standardize the data when we actually loop over iterator and get
 963     # the batches. For now, we just return the iterator as is.
 964     if is_x_eager_iterator and steps is not None:
 965       return x, y, sample_weight
 966 
 967     # If input data is a dataset iterator in graph mode or if it is an eager
 968     # iterator and only one batch of samples is required, we fetch the data
 969     # tensors from the iterator and then standardize them.
 970     if is_x_iterator or is_x_eager_iterator:
 971       try:
 972         if is_x_iterator:
 973           next_element = self._get_iterator_get_next_tensors(x)
 974         else:
 975           next_element = x.get_next()
 976       except errors.OutOfRangeError:
 977         raise RuntimeError('Your dataset iterator ran out of data; '
 978                            'Make sure that your dataset can generate '
 979                            'required number of samples.')
 980 
 981       if (not isinstance(next_element, (list, tuple)) or
 982           len(next_element) not in [2, 3]):
 983         raise ValueError(
 984             'Please provide model inputs as a list or tuple of 2  or 3'
 985             'elements: (input, target) or (input, target, sample_weights)'
 986             'Received %s' % next_element)
 987       if len(next_element) == 2:
 988         x, y = next_element
 989       else:
 990         x, y, sample_weight = next_element
 991     x, y, sample_weights = self._standardize_weights(x, y, sample_weight,
 992                                                      class_weight, batch_size)
 993     return x, y, sample_weights
 994 
 995   def _standardize_weights(self, x, y, sample_weight=None, class_weight=None,
 996                            batch_size=None,):
 997     # TODO(sourabhbajaj): Split input validation from weight standardization.
 998     if sample_weight is not None and class_weight is not None:
 999       logging.warning(
1000           'Received both a `sample_weight` and `class_weight` argument. '
1001           'The `class_weight` argument will be ignored.')
1002     # First, we build/compile the model on the fly if necessary.
1003     all_inputs = []
1004     is_build_called = False
1005     is_compile_called = False
1006     dict_inputs = False
1007     if not self.inputs:
1008       # We need to use `x` to set the model inputs.
1009       # We type-check that `x` and `y` are either single arrays
1010       # or lists of arrays.
1011       if isinstance(x, (list, tuple)):
1012         if not all(isinstance(v, np.ndarray) or
1013                    tensor_util.is_tensor(v) for v in x):
1014           raise ValueError('Please provide as model inputs either a single '
1015                            'array or a list of arrays. You passed: x=' + str(x))
1016         all_inputs += list(x)
1017       elif isinstance(x, dict):
1018         dict_inputs = True
1019         keys = sorted(x.keys())
1020         all_inputs = [x[k] for k in keys]
1021       else:
1022         if not isinstance(x, np.ndarray) and not tensor_util.is_tensor(x):
1023           raise ValueError('Please provide as model inputs either a single '
1024                            'array or a list of arrays. You passed: x=' + str(x))
1025         all_inputs.append(x)
1026 
1027       # Build the model using the retrieved inputs (value or symbolic).
1028       # If values, then in symbolic-mode placeholders will be created
1029       # to match the value shapes.
1030       if not self.inputs:
1031         is_build_called = True
1032         self._set_inputs(x)
1033     else:
1034       dict_inputs = isinstance(self.inputs, dict)
1035 
1036     if y is not None:
1037       if not self.optimizer:
1038         raise RuntimeError('You must compile a model before '
1039                            'training/testing. '
1040                            'Use `model.compile(optimizer, loss)`.')
1041       if not self._is_compiled:
1042         # On-the-fly compilation of the model.
1043         # We need to use `y` to set the model targets.
1044         if isinstance(y, (list, tuple)):
1045           if not all(isinstance(v, np.ndarray) or
1046                      tensor_util.is_tensor(v) for v in y):
1047             raise ValueError('Please provide as model targets either a single '
1048                              'array or a list of arrays. '
1049                              'You passed: y=' + str(y))
1050           all_inputs += list(y)
1051         elif isinstance(y, dict):
1052           raise ValueError('Please do not pass a dictionary as model targets.')
1053         else:
1054           if not isinstance(y, np.ndarray) and not tensor_util.is_tensor(y):
1055             raise ValueError('Please provide as model targets either a single '
1056                              'array or a list of arrays. '
1057                              'You passed: y=' + str(y))
1058           all_inputs.append(y)
1059 
1060         # Typecheck that all inputs are *either* value *or* symbolic.
1061         # TODO(fchollet): this check could be removed in Eager mode?
1062         if any(tensor_util.is_tensor(v) for v in all_inputs):
1063           if not all(tensor_util.is_tensor(v) for v in all_inputs):
1064             raise ValueError('Do not pass inputs that mix Numpy arrays and '
1065                              'TensorFlow tensors. '
1066                              'You passed: x=' + str(x) + '; y=' + str(y))
1067 
1068         if context.executing_eagerly():
1069           target_tensors = None
1070         else:
1071           # Handle target tensors if any passed.
1072           if not isinstance(y, (list, tuple)):
1073             y = [y]
1074           target_tensors = [v for v in y if tensor_util.is_tensor(v)]
1075         is_compile_called = True
1076         self.compile(optimizer=self.optimizer,
1077                      loss=self.loss,
1078                      metrics=self.metrics,
1079                      loss_weights=self.loss_weights,
1080                      target_tensors=target_tensors)
1081 
1082     # In graph mode, if we had just set inputs and targets as symbolic tensors
1083     # by invoking build and compile on the model respectively, we do not have to
1084     # feed anything to the model. Model already has input and target data as
1085     # part of the graph.
1086     # Note: in this case, `any` and `all` are equivalent since we disallow
1087     # mixed symbolic/value inputs.
1088     if (not context.executing_eagerly() and is_build_called and
1089         is_compile_called and
1090         any(tensor_util.is_tensor(v) for v in all_inputs)):
1091       return [], [], []
1092 
1093     # What follows is input validation and standardization to list format,
1094     # in the case where all inputs are value arrays.
1095 
1096     if context.executing_eagerly():
1097       # In eager mode, do not do shape validation
1098       # since the network has no input nodes (placeholders) to be fed.
1099       feed_input_names = self.input_names
1100       feed_input_shapes = None
1101     elif not self._is_graph_network:
1102       # Case: symbolic-mode subclassed network. Do not do shape validation.
1103       feed_input_names = self._feed_input_names
1104       feed_input_shapes = None
1105     else:
1106       # Case: symbolic-mode graph network.
1107       # In this case, we run extensive shape validation checks.
1108       feed_input_names = self._feed_input_names
1109       feed_input_shapes = self._feed_input_shapes
1110 
1111     # Standardize the inputs.
1112     x = training_utils.standardize_input_data(
1113         x,
1114         feed_input_names,
1115         feed_input_shapes,
1116         check_batch_axis=False,  # Don't enforce the batch size.
1117         exception_prefix='input')
1118 
1119     if y is not None:
1120       if not self._is_graph_network:
1121         feed_output_names = self._feed_output_names
1122         feed_output_shapes = None
1123         # Sample weighting not supported in this case.
1124         # TODO(fchollet): consider supporting it.
1125         feed_sample_weight_modes = [None for _ in self.outputs]
1126       else:
1127         feed_output_names = self._feed_output_names
1128         feed_sample_weight_modes = self._feed_sample_weight_modes
1129         feed_output_shapes = []
1130         for output_shape, loss_fn in zip(self._feed_output_shapes,
1131                                          self._feed_loss_fns):
1132           if loss_fn is losses.sparse_categorical_crossentropy:
1133             if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
1134               feed_output_shapes.append(
1135                   (output_shape[0], 1) + output_shape[2:])
1136             else:
1137               feed_output_shapes.append(output_shape[:-1] + (1,))
1138           elif (not hasattr(loss_fn, '__name__') or
1139                 getattr(losses, loss_fn.__name__, None) is None):
1140             # If `loss_fn` is not a function (e.g. callable class)
1141             # or if it not in the `losses` module, then
1142             # it is a user-defined loss and we make no assumptions
1143             # about it.
1144             feed_output_shapes.append(None)
1145           else:
1146             feed_output_shapes.append(output_shape)
1147 
1148       # Standardize the outputs.
1149       y = training_utils.standardize_input_data(
1150           y,
1151           feed_output_names,
1152           feed_output_shapes,
1153           check_batch_axis=False,  # Don't enforce the batch size.
1154           exception_prefix='target')
1155 
1156       # Generate sample-wise weight values given the `sample_weight` and
1157       # `class_weight` arguments.
1158       sample_weights = training_utils.standardize_sample_weights(
1159           sample_weight, feed_output_names)
1160       class_weights = training_utils.standardize_class_weights(
1161           class_weight, feed_output_names)
1162       sample_weights = [
1163           training_utils.standardize_weights(ref, sw, cw, mode)
1164           for (ref, sw, cw, mode) in zip(y, sample_weights, class_weights,
1165                                          feed_sample_weight_modes)
1166       ]
1167       # Check that all arrays have the same length.
1168       if not self._distribution_strategy:
1169         training_utils.check_array_lengths(x, y, sample_weights)
1170         if self._is_graph_network and not context.executing_eagerly():
1171           # Additional checks to avoid users mistakenly using improper loss fns.
1172           training_utils.check_loss_and_target_compatibility(
1173               y, self._feed_loss_fns, feed_output_shapes)
1174     else:
1175       y = []
1176       sample_weights = []
1177 
1178     if self.stateful and batch_size:
1179       # Check that for stateful networks, number of samples is a multiple
1180       # of the static batch size.
1181       if x[0].shape[0] % batch_size != 0:
1182         raise ValueError('In a stateful network, '
1183                          'you should only pass inputs with '
1184                          'a number of samples that can be '
1185                          'divided by the batch size. Found: ' +
1186                          str(x[0].shape[0]) + ' samples')
1187 
1188     # If dictionary inputs were provided, we return a dictionary as well.
1189     if dict_inputs:
1190       x = dict(zip(feed_input_names, x))
1191     return x, y, sample_weights
1192 
1193   @checkpointable.no_automatic_dependency_tracking
1194   def _set_inputs(self, inputs, training=None):
1195     """Set model's input and output specs based on the input data received.
1196 
1197     This is to be used for Model subclasses, which do not know at instantiation
1198     time what their inputs look like.
1199 
1200     Args:
1201       inputs: Single array, or list of arrays. The arrays could be placeholders,
1202         Numpy arrays, or data tensors.
1203         - if placeholders: the model is built on top of these placeholders,
1204           and we expect Numpy data to be fed for them when calling `fit`/etc.
1205         - if Numpy data: we create placeholders matching the shape of the Numpy
1206           arrays. We expect Numpy data to be fed for these placeholders
1207           when calling `fit`/etc.
1208         - if data tensors: the model is built on top of these tensors.
1209           We do not expect any Numpy data to be provided when calling `fit`/etc.
1210       training: Boolean or None. Only relevant in symbolic mode. Specifies
1211         whether to build the model's graph in inference mode (False), training
1212         mode (True), or using the Keras learning phase (None).
1213     Raises:
1214       ValueError: If dict inputs are passed to a Sequential Model where the
1215         first layer isn't FeatureLayer.
1216     """
1217     call_convention = getattr(
1218         self,
1219         '_call_convention',
1220         base_layer.CallConvention.EXPLICIT_INPUTS_ARGUMENT)
1221     if call_convention not in (
1222         base_layer.CallConvention.EXPLICIT_INPUTS_ARGUMENT,
1223         base_layer.CallConvention.SINGLE_POSITIONAL_ARGUMENT):
1224       raise NotImplementedError(
1225           'Subclassed Models without "inputs" (or single positional arguments) '
1226           'in their call() signatures do not yet support shape inference. File '
1227           'a feature request if this limitation bothers you.')
1228     if self.__class__.__name__ == 'Sequential':
1229       if tensor_util.is_tensor(inputs):
1230         input_shape = (None,) + tuple(inputs.get_shape().as_list()[1:])
1231         self.build(input_shape=input_shape)
1232       elif isinstance(inputs, dict):
1233         # We assert that the first layer is a FeatureLayer.
1234         if not training_utils.is_feature_layer(self.layers[0]):
1235           raise ValueError('Passing a dictionary input to a Sequential Model '
1236                            'which doesnt have FeatureLayer as the first layer '
1237                            'is an error')
1238         input_shape = (None,)
1239         self.build(input_shape=input_shape)
1240       else:
1241         input_shape = (None,) + inputs.shape[1:]
1242         self.build(input_shape=input_shape)
1243     if context.executing_eagerly():
1244       self._eager_set_inputs(inputs)
1245     else:
1246       self._symbolic_set_inputs(inputs, training=training)
1247 
1248   @checkpointable.no_automatic_dependency_tracking
1249   def _eager_set_inputs(self, inputs):
1250     """Set model's input and output specs based on the input data received.
1251 
1252     This is to be used for Model subclasses, which do not know at instantiation
1253     time what their inputs look like.
1254 
1255     We assume the number and ndim of outputs
1256     does not change over different calls.
1257 
1258     Args:
1259       inputs: Argument `x` (input data) passed by the user upon first model use.
1260 
1261     Raises:
1262       ValueError: If the model's inputs are already set.
1263     """
1264     assert context.executing_eagerly()
1265     if self.inputs:
1266       raise ValueError('Model inputs are already set.')
1267 
1268     # On-the-fly setting of model inputs/outputs as DeferredTensors,
1269     # to keep track of number of inputs and outputs and their ndim.
1270     model_inputs = training_utils.ModelInputs(inputs)
1271     dummy_input_values = model_inputs.get_input_values()
1272     dummy_output_values = self.call(dummy_input_values)
1273 
1274     self.inputs = model_inputs.get_symbolic_inputs(return_single_as_list=True)
1275     self.input_names = model_inputs.get_input_names()
1276 
1277     dummy_output_values = nest.flatten(dummy_output_values)
1278     self.outputs = [
1279         base_layer.DeferredTensor(shape=(None
1280                                          for _ in v.shape), dtype=v.dtype)
1281         for v in dummy_output_values
1282     ]
1283     self.output_names = [
1284         'output_%d' % (i + 1) for i in range(len(dummy_output_values))]
1285     self.built = True
1286 
1287   @checkpointable.no_automatic_dependency_tracking
1288   def _symbolic_set_inputs(self, inputs, outputs=None, training=None):
1289     """Set model's inputs and output specs based.
1290 
1291     This is to be used for Model subclasses, which do not know at instantiation
1292     time what their inputs look like.
1293 
1294     Args:
1295       inputs: Argument `x` (input data) passed by the user upon first model use.
1296       outputs: None, a data tensor, or a list of data tensors. If None, the
1297         outputs will be determined by invoking self.call(), otherwise the
1298         provided value will be used.
1299       training: Boolean or None. Only relevant in symbolic mode. Specifies
1300         whether to build the model's graph in inference mode (False), training
1301         mode (True), or using the Keras learning phase (None).
1302 
1303     Raises:
1304       ValueError: If the model's inputs are already set.
1305     """
1306     assert not context.executing_eagerly()
1307     if self.inputs:
1308       raise ValueError('Model inputs are already set.')
1309 
1310     # On-the-fly setting of symbolic model inputs (either by using the tensor
1311     # provided, or by creating a placeholder if Numpy data was provided).
1312     model_inputs = training_utils.ModelInputs(inputs)
1313     dummy_input_values = model_inputs.get_symbolic_inputs()
1314     self.inputs = model_inputs.get_symbolic_inputs(return_single_as_list=True)
1315     self.input_names = model_inputs.get_input_names()
1316 
1317     self._feed_inputs = []
1318     self._feed_input_names = []
1319     self._feed_input_shapes = []
1320 
1321     for k, v in model_inputs.as_dict():
1322       if K.is_placeholder(v):
1323         self._feed_inputs.append(v)
1324         self._feed_input_names.append(k)
1325         self._feed_input_shapes.append(K.int_shape(v))
1326 
1327     if outputs is None:
1328       # Obtain symbolic outputs by calling the model.
1329       if self._expects_training_arg:
1330         outputs = self.call(dummy_input_values, training=training)
1331       else:
1332         outputs = self.call(dummy_input_values)
1333 
1334     outputs = nest.flatten(outputs)
1335     self.outputs = outputs
1336     self.output_names = [
1337         'output_%d' % (i + 1) for i in range(len(self.outputs))]
1338     self.built = True
1339 
1340   def fit(self,
1341           x=None,
1342           y=None,
1343           batch_size=None,
1344           epochs=1,
1345           verbose=1,
1346           callbacks=None,
1347           validation_split=0.,
1348           validation_data=None,
1349           shuffle=True,
1350           class_weight=None,
1351           sample_weight=None,
1352           initial_epoch=0,
1353           steps_per_epoch=None,
1354           validation_steps=None,
1355           max_queue_size=10,
1356           workers=1,
1357           use_multiprocessing=False,
1358           **kwargs):
1359     """Trains the model for a fixed number of epochs (iterations on a dataset).
1360 
1361     Arguments:
1362         x: Input data. It could be:
1363           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
1364             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1365           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
1366             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1367           - A dict mapping input names to the corresponding array/tensors,
1368             if the model has named inputs.
1369           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator. Should return a tuple
1370             of either `(inputs, targets)` or
1371             `(inputs, targets, sample_weights)`.
1372           - A generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` returning `(inputs, targets)`
1373             or `(inputs, targets, sample weights)`.
1374         y: Target data. Like the input data `x`,
1375           it could be either Numpy array(s) or TensorFlow tensor(s).
1376           It should be consistent with `x` (you cannot have Numpy inputs and
1377           tensor targets, or inversely). If `x` is a dataset, dataset
1378           iterator, generator, or `keras.utils.Sequence` instance, `y` should
1379           not be specified (since targets will be obtained from `x`).
1380         batch_size: Integer or `None`.
1381             Number of samples per gradient update.
1382             If unspecified, `batch_size` will default to 32.
1383             Do not specify the `batch_size` if your data is in the
1384             form of symbolic tensors, dataset, dataset iterators,
1385             generators, or `keras.utils.Sequence` instances (since they generate
1386             batches).
1387         epochs: Integer. Number of epochs to train the model.
1388             An epoch is an iteration over the entire `x` and `y`
1389             data provided.
1390             Note that in conjunction with `initial_epoch`,
1391             `epochs` is to be understood as "final epoch".
1392             The model is not trained for a number of iterations
1393             given by `epochs`, but merely until the epoch
1394             of index `epochs` is reached.
1395         verbose: Integer. 0, 1, or 2. Verbosity mode.
1396             0 = silent, 1 = progress bar, 2 = one line per epoch.
1397         callbacks: List of `keras.callbacks.Callback` instances.
1398             List of callbacks to apply during training.
1399             See [callbacks](/api_docs/python/tf/keras/callbacks).
1400         validation_split: Float between 0 and 1.
1401             Fraction of the training data to be used as validation data.
1402             The model will set apart this fraction of the training data,
1403             will not train on it, and will evaluate
1404             the loss and any model metrics
1405             on this data at the end of each epoch.
1406             The validation data is selected from the last samples
1407             in the `x` and `y` data provided, before shuffling. This argument is
1408             not supported when `x` is a dataset, dataset iterator, generator or
1409            `keras.utils.Sequence` instance.
1410         validation_data: Data on which to evaluate
1411             the loss and any model metrics at the end of each epoch.
1412             The model will not be trained on this data.
1413             `validation_data` will override `validation_split`.
1414             `validation_data` could be:
1415               - tuple `(x_val, y_val)` of Numpy arrays or tensors
1416               - tuple `(x_val, y_val, val_sample_weights)` of Numpy arrays
1417               - dataset or a dataset iterator
1418         shuffle: Boolean (whether to shuffle the training data
1419             before each epoch) or str (for 'batch').
1420             'batch' is a special option for dealing with the
1421             limitations of HDF5 data; it shuffles in batch-sized chunks.
1422             Has no effect when `steps_per_epoch` is not `None`.
1423         class_weight: Optional dictionary mapping class indices (integers)
1424             to a weight (float) value, used for weighting the loss function
1425             (during training only).
1426             This can be useful to tell the model to
1427             "pay more attention" to samples from
1428             an under-represented class.
1429         sample_weight: Optional Numpy array of weights for
1430             the training samples, used for weighting the loss function
1431             (during training only). You can either pass a flat (1D)
1432             Numpy array with the same length as the input samples
1433             (1:1 mapping between weights and samples),
1434             or in the case of temporal data,
1435             you can pass a 2D array with shape
1436             `(samples, sequence_length)`,
1437             to apply a different weight to every timestep of every sample.
1438             In this case you should make sure to specify
1439             `sample_weight_mode="temporal"` in `compile()`. This argument is not
1440             supported when `x` is a dataset, dataset iterator, generator, or
1441            `keras.utils.Sequence` instance, instead provide the sample_weights
1442             as the third element of `x`.
1443         initial_epoch: Integer.
1444             Epoch at which to start training
1445             (useful for resuming a previous training run).
1446         steps_per_epoch: Integer or `None`.
1447             Total number of steps (batches of samples)
1448             before declaring one epoch finished and starting the
1449             next epoch. When training with input tensors such as
1450             TensorFlow data tensors, the default `None` is equal to
1451             the number of samples in your dataset divided by
1452             the batch size, or 1 if that cannot be determined.
1453         validation_steps: Only relevant if `steps_per_epoch`
1454             is specified. Total number of steps (batches of samples)
1455             to validate before stopping.
1456         max_queue_size: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence`
1457             input only. Maximum size for the generator queue.
1458             If unspecified, `max_queue_size` will default to 10.
1459         workers: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` input
1460             only. Maximum number of processes to spin up
1461             when using process-based threading. If unspecified, `workers`
1462             will default to 1. If 0, will execute the generator on the main
1463             thread.
1464         use_multiprocessing: Boolean. Used for generator or
1465             `keras.utils.Sequence` input only. If `True`, use process-based
1466             threading. If unspecified, `use_multiprocessing` will default to
1467             `False`. Note that because this implementation relies on
1468             multiprocessing, you should not pass non-picklable arguments to
1469             the generator as they can't be passed easily to children processes.
1470         **kwargs: Used for backwards compatibility.
1471 
1472     Returns:
1473         A `History` object. Its `History.history` attribute is
1474         a record of training loss values and metrics values
1475         at successive epochs, as well as validation loss values
1476         and validation metrics values (if applicable).
1477 
1478     Raises:
1479         RuntimeError: If the model was never compiled.
1480         ValueError: In case of mismatch between the provided input data
1481             and what the model expects.
1482     """
1483     # TODO(fchollet): this method may be creating reference cycles, which would
1484     # lead to accumulating garbage in memory when called in a loop. Investigate.
1485 
1486     if data_utils.is_generator_or_sequence(x):
1487       training_utils.check_generator_arguments(y, sample_weight)
1488       return self.fit_generator(
1489           x,
1490           steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
1491           epochs=epochs,
1492           verbose=verbose,
1493           callbacks=callbacks,
1494           validation_data=validation_data,
1495           validation_steps=validation_steps,
1496           class_weight=class_weight,
1497           max_queue_size=max_queue_size,
1498           workers=workers,
1499           use_multiprocessing=use_multiprocessing,
1500           shuffle=shuffle,
1501           initial_epoch=initial_epoch)
1502 
1503     # Backwards compatibility
1504     if batch_size is None and steps_per_epoch is None:
1505       batch_size = 32
1506     # Legacy support
1507     if 'nb_epoch' in kwargs:
1508       logging.warning(
1509           'The `nb_epoch` argument in `fit` '
1510           'has been renamed `epochs`.')
1511       epochs = kwargs.pop('nb_epoch')
1512     if kwargs:
1513       raise TypeError('Unrecognized keyword arguments: ' + str(kwargs))
1514 
1515     # Validate and standardize user data.
1516     if self._distribution_strategy:
1517       distributed_training_utils.validate_callbacks(callbacks)
1518 
1519       distributed_training_utils.validate_inputs(
1520           x, y, self._distribution_strategy)
1521 
1522       first_x_value = nest.flatten(x)[0]
1523       if not steps_per_epoch and isinstance(first_x_value, np.ndarray):
1524         steps_per_epoch = distributed_training_utils.get_input_batch_params(
1525             first_x_value, batch_size, self._distribution_strategy)
1526 
1527     x, y, sample_weights = self._standardize_user_data(
1528         x,
1529         y,
1530         sample_weight=sample_weight,
1531         class_weight=class_weight,
1532         batch_size=batch_size,
1533         check_steps=True,
1534         steps_name='steps_per_epoch',
1535         steps=steps_per_epoch,
1536         validation_split=validation_split)
1537 
1538     # Prepare validation data.
1539     if validation_data:
1540       if (isinstance(validation_data, iterator_ops.Iterator) or
1541           isinstance(validation_data, iterator_ops.EagerIterator) or
1542           isinstance(validation_data, dataset_ops.Dataset)):
1543         val_x = validation_data
1544         val_y = None
1545         val_sample_weight = None
1546       elif len(validation_data) == 2:
1547         val_x, val_y = validation_data  # pylint: disable=unpacking-non-sequence
1548         val_sample_weight = None
1549       elif len(validation_data) == 3:
1550         val_x, val_y, val_sample_weight = validation_data  # pylint: disable=unpacking-non-sequence
1551       else:
1552         raise ValueError(
1553             'When passing a `validation_data` argument, '
1554             'it must contain either 2 items (x_val, y_val), '
1555             'or 3 items (x_val, y_val, val_sample_weights), '
1556             'or alternatively it could be a dataset or a '
1557             'dataset or a dataset iterator. '
1558             'However we received `validation_data=%s`' % validation_data)
1559 
1560       # Validate and standardize validation data.
1561       if self._distribution_strategy:
1562         distributed_training_utils.validate_inputs(
1563             val_x, val_y, self._distribution_strategy)
1564         first_valx_value = nest.flatten(val_x)[0]
1565         if not validation_steps and isinstance(first_valx_value, np.ndarray):
1566           validation_steps = distributed_training_utils.get_input_batch_params(
1567               first_valx_value, batch_size, self._distribution_strategy)
1568 
1569       val_x, val_y, val_sample_weights = self._standardize_user_data(
1570           val_x,
1571           val_y,
1572           sample_weight=val_sample_weight,
1573           batch_size=batch_size,
1574           steps=validation_steps)
1575 
1576     elif validation_split and 0. < validation_split < 1.:
1577       if training_utils.has_symbolic_tensors(x):
1578         raise ValueError('If your data is in the form of symbolic tensors, '
1579                          'you cannot use `validation_split`.')
1580       if hasattr(x[0], 'shape'):
1581         split_at = int(x[0].shape[0] * (1. - validation_split))
1582       else:
1583         split_at = int(len(x[0]) * (1. - validation_split))
1584       x, val_x = (slice_arrays(x, 0, split_at), slice_arrays(x, split_at))
1585       y, val_y = (slice_arrays(y, 0, split_at), slice_arrays(y, split_at))
1586       sample_weights, val_sample_weights = (slice_arrays(
1587           sample_weights, 0, split_at), slice_arrays(sample_weights, split_at))
1588     elif validation_steps:
1589       val_x = []
1590       val_y = []
1591       val_sample_weights = []
1592     else:
1593       val_x = None
1594       val_y = None
1595       val_sample_weights = None
1596 
1597     if context.executing_eagerly():
1598       return training_eager.fit_loop(
1599           self,
1600           inputs=x,
1601           targets=y,
1602           sample_weights=sample_weights,
1603           class_weight=class_weight,
1604           batch_size=batch_size,
1605           epochs=epochs,
1606           verbose=verbose,
1607           callbacks=callbacks,
1608           val_inputs=val_x,
1609           val_targets=val_y,
1610           val_sample_weights=val_sample_weights,
1611           shuffle=shuffle,
1612           initial_epoch=initial_epoch,
1613           steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
1614           validation_steps=validation_steps)
1615     elif self._distribution_strategy:
1616       return training_distributed.fit_loop(
1617           self, x,
1618           epochs=epochs,
1619           verbose=verbose,
1620           callbacks=callbacks,
1621           val_iterator=val_x,
1622           initial_epoch=initial_epoch,
1623           steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
1624           validation_steps=validation_steps)
1625     else:
1626       return training_arrays.fit_loop(
1627           self, x, y,
1628           sample_weights=sample_weights,
1629           batch_size=batch_size,
1630           epochs=epochs,
1631           verbose=verbose,
1632           callbacks=callbacks,
1633           val_inputs=val_x,
1634           val_targets=val_y,
1635           val_sample_weights=val_sample_weights,
1636           shuffle=shuffle,
1637           initial_epoch=initial_epoch,
1638           steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
1639           validation_steps=validation_steps)
1640 
1641   def evaluate(self,
1642                x=None,
1643                y=None,
1644                batch_size=None,
1645                verbose=1,
1646                sample_weight=None,
1647                steps=None,
1648                max_queue_size=10,
1649                workers=1,
1650                use_multiprocessing=False):
1651     """Returns the loss value & metrics values for the model in test mode.
1652 
1653     Computation is done in batches.
1654 
1655     Arguments:
1656         x: Input data. It could be:
1657           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
1658             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1659           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
1660             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1661           - A dict mapping input names to the corresponding array/tensors,
1662             if the model has named inputs.
1663           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
1664           - A generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` instance.
1665         y: Target data. Like the input data `x`,
1666           it could be either Numpy array(s) or TensorFlow tensor(s).
1667           It should be consistent with `x` (you cannot have Numpy inputs and
1668           tensor targets, or inversely).
1669           If `x` is a dataset, dataset iterator, generator or
1670           `keras.utils.Sequence` instance, `y` should not be specified (since
1671           targets will be obtained from the iterator/dataset).
1672         batch_size: Integer or `None`.
1673             Number of samples per gradient update.
1674             If unspecified, `batch_size` will default to 32.
1675             Do not specify the `batch_size` is your data is in the
1676             form of symbolic tensors, dataset, dataset iterators,
1677             generators, or `keras.utils.Sequence` instances (since they generate
1678             batches).
1679         verbose: 0 or 1. Verbosity mode.
1680             0 = silent, 1 = progress bar.
1681         sample_weight: Optional Numpy array of weights for
1682             the test samples, used for weighting the loss function.
1683             You can either pass a flat (1D)
1684             Numpy array with the same length as the input samples
1685             (1:1 mapping between weights and samples),
1686             or in the case of temporal data,
1687             you can pass a 2D array with shape
1688             `(samples, sequence_length)`,
1689             to apply a different weight to every timestep of every sample.
1690             In this case you should make sure to specify
1691             `sample_weight_mode="temporal"` in `compile()`. This argument is not
1692             supported when `x` is a dataset or a dataset iterator, instead pass
1693             sample weights as the third element of `x`.
1694         steps: Integer or `None`.
1695             Total number of steps (batches of samples)
1696             before declaring the evaluation round finished.
1697             Ignored with the default value of `None`.
1698         max_queue_size: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence`
1699             input only. Maximum size for the generator queue.
1700             If unspecified, `max_queue_size` will default to 10.
1701         workers: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` input
1702             only. Maximum number of processes to spin up when using
1703             process-based threading. If unspecified, `workers` will default
1704             to 1. If 0, will execute the generator on the main thread.
1705         use_multiprocessing: Boolean. Used for generator or
1706             `keras.utils.Sequence` input only. If `True`, use process-based
1707             threading. If unspecified, `use_multiprocessing` will default to
