1708             `False`. Note that because this implementation relies on
1709             multiprocessing, you should not pass non-picklable arguments to
1710             the generator as they can't be passed easily to children processes.
1711 
1712     Returns:
1713         Scalar test loss (if the model has a single output and no metrics)
1714         or list of scalars (if the model has multiple outputs
1715         and/or metrics). The attribute `model.metrics_names` will give you
1716         the display labels for the scalar outputs.
1717 
1718     Raises:
1719         ValueError: in case of invalid arguments.
1720     """
1721     if data_utils.is_generator_or_sequence(x):
1722       training_utils.check_generator_arguments(y, sample_weight)
1723       return self.evaluate_generator(
1724           x,
1725           steps=steps,
1726           verbose=verbose,
1727           max_queue_size=max_queue_size,
1728           workers=workers,
1729           use_multiprocessing=use_multiprocessing)
1730 
1731     # Backwards compatibility.
1732     if batch_size is None and steps is None:
1733       batch_size = 32
1734 
1735     # Validate and standardize user data.
1736     if self._distribution_strategy:
1737       distributed_training_utils.validate_inputs(
1738           x, y, self._distribution_strategy)
1739       first_x_value = nest.flatten(x)[0]
1740       if isinstance(first_x_value, np.ndarray) and not steps:
1741         steps = distributed_training_utils.get_input_batch_params(
1742             first_x_value, batch_size, self._distribution_strategy)
1743 
1744     x, y, sample_weights = self._standardize_user_data(
1745         x,
1746         y,
1747         sample_weight=sample_weight,
1748         batch_size=batch_size,
1749         check_steps=True,
1750         steps_name='steps',
1751         steps=steps)
1752 
1753     if context.executing_eagerly():
1754       return training_eager.test_loop(
1755           self,
1756           inputs=x,
1757           targets=y,
1758           sample_weights=sample_weights,
1759           batch_size=batch_size,
1760           verbose=verbose,
1761           steps=steps)
1762     elif self._distribution_strategy:
1763       return training_distributed.test_loop(
1764           self,
1765           iterator=x,
1766           verbose=verbose,
1767           steps=steps)
1768     else:
1769       return training_arrays.test_loop(
1770           self,
1771           inputs=x,
1772           targets=y,
1773           sample_weights=sample_weights,
1774           batch_size=batch_size,
1775           verbose=verbose,
1776           steps=steps)
1777 
1778   def predict(self,
1779               x,
1780               batch_size=None,
1781               verbose=0,
1782               steps=None,
1783               max_queue_size=10,
1784               workers=1,
1785               use_multiprocessing=False):
1786     """Generates output predictions for the input samples.
1787 
1788     Computation is done in batches.
1789 
1790     Arguments:
1791          x: Input samples. It could be:
1792           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
1793             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1794           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
1795             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1796           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
1797           - A generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` instance.
1798         batch_size: Integer or `None`.
1799             Number of samples per gradient update.
1800             If unspecified, `batch_size` will default to 32.
1801             Do not specify the `batch_size` is your data is in the
1802             form of symbolic tensors, dataset, dataset iterators,
1803             generators, or `keras.utils.Sequence` instances (since they generate
1804             batches).
1805         verbose: Verbosity mode, 0 or 1.
1806         steps: Total number of steps (batches of samples)
1807             before declaring the prediction round finished.
1808             Ignored with the default value of `None`.
1809         max_queue_size: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence`
1810             input only. Maximum size for the generator queue.
1811             If unspecified, `max_queue_size` will default to 10.
1812         workers: Integer. Used for generator or `keras.utils.Sequence` input
1813             only. Maximum number of processes to spin up when using
1814             process-based threading. If unspecified, `workers` will default
1815             to 1. If 0, will execute the generator on the main thread.
1816         use_multiprocessing: Boolean. Used for generator or
1817             `keras.utils.Sequence` input only. If `True`, use process-based
1818             threading. If unspecified, `use_multiprocessing` will default to
1819             `False`. Note that because this implementation relies on
1820             multiprocessing, you should not pass non-picklable arguments to
1821             the generator as they can't be passed easily to children processes.
1822 
1823 
1824     Returns:
1825         Numpy array(s) of predictions.
1826 
1827     Raises:
1828         ValueError: In case of mismatch between the provided
1829             input data and the model's expectations,
1830             or in case a stateful model receives a number of samples
1831             that is not a multiple of the batch size.
1832     """
1833     if data_utils.is_generator_or_sequence(x):
1834       return self.predict_generator(
1835           x,
1836           steps=steps,
1837           verbose=verbose,
1838           max_queue_size=max_queue_size,
1839           workers=workers,
1840           use_multiprocessing=use_multiprocessing)
1841 
1842     # Backwards compatibility.
1843     if batch_size is None and steps is None:
1844       batch_size = 32
1845 
1846     if self._distribution_strategy:
1847       # Turn off prefetching since this is currently not deterministic. Once
1848       # b/112498930 is fixed we can turn it back on.
1849       # `_prefetch_on_device` is currently a property of only
1850       # `MirroredStrategy`.
1851       if hasattr(self._distribution_strategy, '_prefetch_on_device'):
1852         self._distribution_strategy._prefetch_on_device = False  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1853       distributed_training_utils.validate_inputs(
1854           x, None, self._distribution_strategy)
1855       first_x_value = nest.flatten(x)[0]
1856       if isinstance(first_x_value, np.ndarray) and not steps:
1857         steps = distributed_training_utils.get_input_batch_params(
1858             first_x_value, batch_size, self._distribution_strategy)
1859 
1860     # Validate and standardize user data.
1861     # TODO(anjalisridhar): We don't pass batch_size here for some reason. This
1862     # means that we end up calculating it twice which we should avoid.
1863     x, _, _ = self._standardize_user_data(
1864         x, check_steps=True, steps_name='steps', steps=steps)
1865 
1866     if context.executing_eagerly():
1867       return training_eager.predict_loop(
1868           self, x, batch_size=batch_size, verbose=verbose, steps=steps)
1869     elif self._distribution_strategy:
1870       results = training_distributed.predict_loop(
1871           self, x, verbose=verbose, steps=steps)
1872       # Turn prefetching back on since we turned it off previously.
1873       if hasattr(self._distribution_strategy, '_prefetch_on_device'):
1874         self._distribution_strategy._prefetch_on_device = True  # pylint: disable=protected-access
1875       return results
1876     else:
1877       return training_arrays.predict_loop(
1878           self, x, batch_size=batch_size, verbose=verbose, steps=steps)
1879 
1880   def train_on_batch(self, x, y=None, sample_weight=None, class_weight=None):
1881     """Runs a single gradient update on a single batch of data.
1882 
1883     Arguments:
1884         x: Input data. It could be:
1885           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
1886             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1887           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
1888             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1889           - A dict mapping input names to the corresponding array/tensors,
1890             if the model has named inputs.
1891           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
1892         y: Target data. Like the input data `x`,
1893           it could be either Numpy array(s) or TensorFlow tensor(s).
1894           It should be consistent with `x` (you cannot have Numpy inputs and
1895           tensor targets, or inversely). If `x` is a dataset or a
1896           dataset iterator, `y` should not be specified
1897           (since targets will be obtained from the iterator).
1898         sample_weight: Optional array of the same length as x, containing
1899             weights to apply to the model's loss for each sample.
1900             In the case of temporal data, you can pass a 2D array
1901             with shape (samples, sequence_length),
1902             to apply a different weight to every timestep of every sample.
1903             In this case you should make sure to specify
1904             sample_weight_mode="temporal" in compile(). This argument is not
1905             supported when `x` is a dataset or a dataset iterator.
1906         class_weight: Optional dictionary mapping
1907             class indices (integers) to
1908             a weight (float) to apply to the model's loss for the samples
1909             from this class during training.
1910             This can be useful to tell the model to "pay more attention" to
1911             samples from an under-represented class.
1912 
1913     Returns:
1914         Scalar training loss
1915         (if the model has a single output and no metrics)
1916         or list of scalars (if the model has multiple outputs
1917         and/or metrics). The attribute `model.metrics_names` will give you
1918         the display labels for the scalar outputs.
1919 
1920     Raises:
1921       ValueError: In case of invalid user-provided arguments.
1922     """
1923     if self._distribution_strategy:
1924       raise NotImplementedError('`train_on_batch` is not supported for models '
1925                                 'compiled with DistributionStrategy.')
1926     # Validate and standardize user data.
1927     x, y, sample_weights = self._standardize_user_data(
1928         x, y, sample_weight=sample_weight, class_weight=class_weight)
1929 
1930     if context.executing_eagerly():
1931       outputs = training_eager.train_on_batch(
1932           self, x, y, sample_weights=sample_weights)
1933     else:
1934       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
1935         ins = x + y + sample_weights + [1]
1936       else:
1937         ins = x + y + sample_weights
1938 
1939       self._make_train_function()
1940       outputs = self.train_function(ins)
1941 
1942     if len(outputs) == 1:
1943       return outputs[0]
1944     return outputs
1945 
1946   def test_on_batch(self, x, y=None, sample_weight=None):
1947     """Test the model on a single batch of samples.
1948 
1949     Arguments:
1950         x: Input data. It could be:
1951           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
1952             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1953           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
1954             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
1955           - A dict mapping input names to the corresponding array/tensors,
1956             if the model has named inputs.
1957           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
1958         y: Target data. Like the input data `x`,
1959           it could be either Numpy array(s) or TensorFlow tensor(s).
1960           It should be consistent with `x` (you cannot have Numpy inputs and
1961           tensor targets, or inversely). If `x` is a dataset or a
1962           dataset iterator, `y` should not be specified
1963           (since targets will be obtained from the iterator).
1964         sample_weight: Optional array of the same length as x, containing
1965             weights to apply to the model's loss for each sample.
1966             In the case of temporal data, you can pass a 2D array
1967             with shape (samples, sequence_length),
1968             to apply a different weight to every timestep of every sample.
1969             In this case you should make sure to specify
1970             sample_weight_mode="temporal" in compile(). This argument is not
1971             supported when `x` is a dataset or a dataset iterator.
1972 
1973     Returns:
1974         Scalar test loss (if the model has a single output and no metrics)
1975         or list of scalars (if the model has multiple outputs
1976         and/or metrics). The attribute `model.metrics_names` will give you
1977         the display labels for the scalar outputs.
1978 
1979     Raises:
1980         ValueError: In case of invalid user-provided arguments.
1981     """
1982     if self._distribution_strategy:
1983       raise NotImplementedError('`test_on_batch` is not supported for models '
1984                                 'compiled with DistributionStrategy.')
1985     # Validate and standardize user data.
1986     x, y, sample_weights = self._standardize_user_data(
1987         x, y, sample_weight=sample_weight)
1988 
1989     if context.executing_eagerly():
1990       outputs = training_eager.test_on_batch(
1991           self, x, y, sample_weights=sample_weights)
1992     else:
1993       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
1994         ins = x + y + sample_weights + [0]
1995       else:
1996         ins = x + y + sample_weights
1997       self._make_test_function()
1998       outputs = self.test_function(ins)
1999 
2000     if len(outputs) == 1:
2001       return outputs[0]
2002     return outputs
2003 
2004   def predict_on_batch(self, x):
2005     """Returns predictions for a single batch of samples.
2006 
2007     Arguments:
2008         x: Input data. It could be:
2009           - A Numpy array (or array-like), or a list of arrays
2010             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
2011           - A TensorFlow tensor, or a list of tensors
2012             (in case the model has multiple inputs).
2013           - A `tf.data` dataset or a dataset iterator.
2014 
2015     Returns:
2016         Numpy array(s) of predictions.
2017 
2018     Raises:
2019         ValueError: In case of mismatch between given number of inputs and
2020           expectations of the model.
2021     """
2022     if self._distribution_strategy:
2023       raise NotImplementedError('`predict_on_batch` is not supported for '
2024                                 'models compiled with DistributionStrategy.')
2025     # Validate and standardize user data.
2026     inputs, _, _ = self._standardize_user_data(x)
2027     if context.executing_eagerly():
2028       if (isinstance(x, iterator_ops.EagerIterator) or
2029           (isinstance(x, dataset_ops.Dataset) and context.executing_eagerly())):
2030         inputs = training_utils.cast_if_floating_dtype(inputs)
2031       else:
2032         inputs = [
2033             ops.convert_to_tensor(val, dtype=K.floatx()) for val in inputs
2034         ]
2035       return self(inputs)  # pylint: disable=not-callable
2036 
2037     if not context.executing_eagerly():
2038       if self.uses_learning_phase and not isinstance(K.learning_phase(), int):
2039         ins = inputs + [0]
2040       else:
2041         ins = inputs
2042 
2043       self._make_predict_function()
2044       outputs = self.predict_function(ins)
2045 
2046       if len(outputs) == 1:
2047         return outputs[0]
2048       return outputs
2049 
2050   def fit_generator(self,
2051                     generator,
2052                     steps_per_epoch=None,
2053                     epochs=1,
2054                     verbose=1,
2055                     callbacks=None,
2056                     validation_data=None,
2057                     validation_steps=None,
2058                     class_weight=None,
2059                     max_queue_size=10,
2060                     workers=1,
2061                     use_multiprocessing=False,
2062                     shuffle=True,
2063                     initial_epoch=0):
2064     """Fits the model on data yielded batch-by-batch by a Python generator.
2065 
2066     The generator is run in parallel to the model, for efficiency.
2067     For instance, this allows you to do real-time data augmentation
2068     on images on CPU in parallel to training your model on GPU.
2069 
2070     The use of `keras.utils.Sequence` guarantees the ordering
2071     and guarantees the single use of every input per epoch when
2072     using `use_multiprocessing=True`.
2073 
2074     Arguments:
2075         generator: A generator or an instance of `Sequence`
2076           (`keras.utils.Sequence`)
2077             object in order to avoid duplicate data
2078             when using multiprocessing.
2079             The output of the generator must be either
2080             - a tuple `(inputs, targets)`
2081             - a tuple `(inputs, targets, sample_weights)`.
2082             This tuple (a single output of the generator) makes a single batch.
2083             Therefore, all arrays in this tuple must have the same length (equal
2084             to the size of this batch). Different batches may have different
2085               sizes.
2086             For example, the last batch of the epoch is commonly smaller than
2087               the
2088             others, if the size of the dataset is not divisible by the batch
2089               size.
2090             The generator is expected to loop over its data
2091             indefinitely. An epoch finishes when `steps_per_epoch`
2092             batches have been seen by the model.
2093         steps_per_epoch: Total number of steps (batches of samples)
2094             to yield from `generator` before declaring one epoch
2095             finished and starting the next epoch. It should typically
2096             be equal to the number of samples of your dataset
2097             divided by the batch size.
2098             Optional for `Sequence`: if unspecified, will use
2099             the `len(generator)` as a number of steps.
2100         epochs: Integer, total number of iterations on the data.
2101         verbose: Verbosity mode, 0, 1, or 2.
2102         callbacks: List of callbacks to be called during training.
2103         validation_data: This can be either
2104             - a generator for the validation data
2105             - a tuple (inputs, targets)
2106             - a tuple (inputs, targets, sample_weights).
2107         validation_steps: Only relevant if `validation_data`
2108             is a generator. Total number of steps (batches of samples)
2109             to yield from `generator` before stopping.
2110             Optional for `Sequence`: if unspecified, will use
2111             the `len(validation_data)` as a number of steps.
2112         class_weight: Dictionary mapping class indices to a weight
2113             for the class.
2114         max_queue_size: Integer. Maximum size for the generator queue.
2115             If unspecified, `max_queue_size` will default to 10.
2116         workers: Integer. Maximum number of processes to spin up
2117             when using process-based threading.
2118             If unspecified, `workers` will default to 1. If 0, will
2119             execute the generator on the main thread.
2120         use_multiprocessing: Boolean.
2121             If `True`, use process-based threading.
2122             If unspecified, `use_multiprocessing` will default to `False`.
2123             Note that because this implementation relies on multiprocessing,
2124             you should not pass non-picklable arguments to the generator
2125             as they can't be passed easily to children processes.
2126         shuffle: Boolean. Whether to shuffle the order of the batches at
2127             the beginning of each epoch. Only used with instances
2128             of `Sequence` (`keras.utils.Sequence`).
2129             Has no effect when `steps_per_epoch` is not `None`.
2130         initial_epoch: Epoch at which to start training
2131             (useful for resuming a previous training run)
2132 
2133     Returns:
2134         A `History` object.
2135 
2136     Example:
2137 
2138     ```python
2139         def generate_arrays_from_file(path):
2140             while 1:
2141                 f = open(path)
2142                 for line in f:
2143                     # create numpy arrays of input data
2144                     # and labels, from each line in the file
2145                     x1, x2, y = process_line(line)
2146                     yield ({'input_1': x1, 'input_2': x2}, {'output': y})
2147                 f.close()
2148 
2149         model.fit_generator(generate_arrays_from_file('/my_file.txt'),
2150                             steps_per_epoch=10000, epochs=10)
2151     ```
2152     Raises:
2153         ValueError: In case the generator yields data in an invalid format.
2154     """
2155     if self._distribution_strategy:
2156       raise NotImplementedError('`fit_generator` is not supported for '
2157                                 'models compiled with DistributionStrategy.')
2158 
2159     if not self.built and not self._is_graph_network:
2160       raise NotImplementedError(
2161           '`fit_generator` is not yet enabled for unbuilt Model subclasses')
2162 
2163     return training_generator.fit_generator(
2164         self,
2165         generator,
2166         steps_per_epoch=steps_per_epoch,
2167         epochs=epochs,
2168         verbose=verbose,
2169         callbacks=callbacks,
2170         validation_data=validation_data,
2171         validation_steps=validation_steps,
2172         class_weight=class_weight,
2173         max_queue_size=max_queue_size,
2174         workers=workers,
2175         use_multiprocessing=use_multiprocessing,
2176         shuffle=shuffle,
2177         initial_epoch=initial_epoch)
2178 
2179   def evaluate_generator(self,
2180                          generator,
2181                          steps=None,
2182                          max_queue_size=10,
2183                          workers=1,
2184                          use_multiprocessing=False,
2185                          verbose=0):
2186     """Evaluates the model on a data generator.
2187 
2188     The generator should return the same kind of data
2189     as accepted by `test_on_batch`.
2190 
2191     Arguments:
2192         generator: Generator yielding tuples (inputs, targets)
2193             or (inputs, targets, sample_weights)
2194             or an instance of `keras.utils.Sequence`
2195             object in order to avoid duplicate data
2196             when using multiprocessing.
2197         steps: Total number of steps (batches of samples)
2198             to yield from `generator` before stopping.
2199             Optional for `Sequence`: if unspecified, will use
2200             the `len(generator)` as a number of steps.
2201         max_queue_size: maximum size for the generator queue
2202         workers: Integer. Maximum number of processes to spin up
2203             when using process-based threading.
2204             If unspecified, `workers` will default to 1. If 0, will
2205             execute the generator on the main thread.
2206         use_multiprocessing: Boolean.
2207             If `True`, use process-based threading.
2208             If unspecified, `use_multiprocessing` will default to `False`.
2209             Note that because this implementation relies on multiprocessing,
2210             you should not pass non-picklable arguments to the generator
2211             as they can't be passed easily to children processes.
2212         verbose: Verbosity mode, 0 or 1.
2213 
2214     Returns:
2215         Scalar test loss (if the model has a single output and no metrics)
2216         or list of scalars (if the model has multiple outputs
2217         and/or metrics). The attribute `model.metrics_names` will give you
2218         the display labels for the scalar outputs.
2219 
2220     Raises:
2221         ValueError: in case of invalid arguments.
2222 
2223     Raises:
2224         ValueError: In case the generator yields data in an invalid format.
2225     """
2226     if self._distribution_strategy:
2227       raise NotImplementedError('`evaluate_generator` is not supported for '
2228                                 'models compiled with DistributionStrategy.')
2229 
2230     if not self.built and not self._is_graph_network:
2231       raise NotImplementedError(
2232           '`evaluate_generator` is not yet enabled for '
2233           'unbuilt Model subclasses')
2234 
2235     return training_generator.evaluate_generator(
2236         self,
2237         generator,
2238         steps=steps,
2239         max_queue_size=max_queue_size,
2240         workers=workers,
2241         use_multiprocessing=use_multiprocessing,
2242         verbose=verbose)
2243

2299 
2300   def _get_callback_model(self):
2301     """Returns the Callback Model for this Model."""
2302 
2303     if hasattr(self, '_replicated_model') and self._replicated_model:
2304       # When using training_distributed, we set the callback model
2305       # to an instance of the `DistributedModel` that we create in
2306       # the `compile` call. The `DistributedModel` is initialized
2307       # with the first replicated model. We need to set the callback
2308       # model to a DistributedModel to allow us to override saving
2309       # and loading weights when we checkpoint the model during training.
2310       return self._replicated_model
2311     if hasattr(self, 'callback_model') and self.callback_model:
2312       return self.callback_model
2313     return self
2314 
2315   def _make_callback_model(self):
2316     first_replicated_model = self._distribution_strategy.unwrap(
2317         self._grouped_model)[0]
2318     # We initialize the callback model with the first replicated model.
2319     self._replicated_model = DistributedCallbackModel(first_replicated_model)
2320     self._replicated_model.set_original_model(self)
2321 
2322 
2323 class DistributedCallbackModel(Model):
2324   """Model that is used for callbacks with DistributionStrategy."""
2325 
2326   def __init__(self, model):
2327     super(DistributedCallbackModel, self).__init__()
2328     # TODO(anjalisridhar): Right now the only attributes set are the layer and
2329     # weights. We may need to set additional attributes as needed since we have
2330     # not called compile on this model.
2331 
2332   def set_original_model(self, orig_model):
2333     self._original_model = orig_model
2334 
2335   def save_weights(self, filepath, overwrite=True, save_format=None):
2336     self._replicated_model.save_weights(filepath, overwrite=overwrite,
2337                                         save_format=save_format)
2338 
2339   def save(self, filepath, overwrite=True, include_optimizer=True):
2340     # save weights from the distributed model to the original model
2341     distributed_model_weights = self.get_weights()
2342     self._original_model.set_weights(distributed_model_weights)
2343     # TODO(anjalisridhar): Do we need to save the original model here?
2344     # Saving the first replicated model works as well.
2345     self._original_model.save(filepath, overwrite=True, include_optimizer=False)
2346 
2347   def load_weights(self, filepath, by_name=False):
2348     self._original_model.load_weights(filepath, by_name=False)
2349     # Copy the weights from the original model to each of the replicated models.
2350     orig_model_weights = self._original_model.get_weights()
2351     distributed_training_utils.set_weights(
2352         self._original_model._distribution_strategy, self,  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2353         orig_model_weights)
2354 
2355   def __getattr__(self, item):
2356     # Whitelisted atttributes of the model that can be accessed by the user
2357     # during a callback.
2358     if item not in ['_setattr_tracking']:
2359       logging.warning('You are accessing attribute ' + item + 'of the '
2360                       'DistributedCallbackModel that may not have been set '
2361                       'correctly.')
